Curtius, 5.1.43</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note7" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref7
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">7</A>
Arrian, 3.16.4<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->. Some of these administrative arrangements may have been made at Susa
(Arrian, 3.16.6‑11)<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note8" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">8</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#1.44
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 5.1.44</A>;
Arrian, 3.16.5<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->. Armenia had not been and was not to be conquered at this time, and Mithrines did not enter upon his <SPAN CLASS="whole">governor</SPAN>&shy;ship (Berve, <I>Alexanderreich</I>, 2, no. 524).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note9" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref9
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">9</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#1.45
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 5.1.45</A>. A mina contained one hundred drachmae,


<A ID="p303x"></A>and was one-sixtieth of a talent. The pay of Alexander's army is unknown, but that of a <SPAN CLASS="whole">cavalry&shy;man</SPAN> must have been at least two drachmae a day. <SPAN CLASS="small">IG</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="smaller">II<SPAN CLASS="superscript">2</SPAN></SPAN>.329 shows that an Athenian hypaspist serving in the League troops with Alexander received a drachma a day from the city. Cp. W. Rüstow, H. Köchly, <I>Geschichte der griechischen Kriegskunst</I> (1852), 262 f.; Berve, <I>Alexanderreich</I>, 1.193‑196.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note10" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">10</A>
Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#1.39
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(5.1.39‑42)
	</A>
gives the same figures, with the exception of specifying 380 cavalry. These troops must have been sent by Antipater before trouble was anticipated in Greece. They had been recruited by Amyntas (<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17C*.html#49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 49.1</A>;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#1.40
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 5.1.40</A>). The Trallians were a Thracian people.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note11" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref11
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">11</A>
The same figure is given by
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#1.42
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 5.1.42</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note12" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref12
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">12</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#2.1
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 5.2.1</A>. This district lay parallel to Babylonia on the left bank of the Tigris.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note13" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref13
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">13</A>
Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#2.2
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(5.2.2‑7)
	</A>
describes these measures in more detail, but without satisfying our desire for specific military information. It may be that Alexander was re-organizing his dispositions in view of the impending mountain and steppe warfare, requiring increased fire-power and mobility (Rüstow-Köchly, <I>op. cit.</I> 252).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note14" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref14
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">14</A>
Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#2.8
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(5.2.8)
	</A>
and Arrian
(3.16.9)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->
give his name as Abulites, and say that Alexander left him in Susa as governor.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note15" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref15
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">15</A>
This rumour is not mentioned by the other Alexander historians, and its source is unknown.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note16" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref16
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">16</A>
Justin
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte11.html#14
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(11.14.9)</A>
and Plutarch
(<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/5.html#36
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Alexander</I>, 36.1</A>: coined money) give the same figure as Diodorus; Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#2.11
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(5.2.11)
	</A>
and Arrian
(3.16.7)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->
give 50,000 talents. The daric was the standard Persian gold coin with an image of the king on one side depicted as an archer. The name was popularly derived from that of Dareius I, who first minted them (cp. E. S. G. Robinson, <I>Numismatic Chronicle</I>, 18, 958, 187‑193).<!-- Loeb has period inside parenthesis -->


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note17" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">17</A>
The story is told also by Curtius,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#2.13
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
5.2.13‑15</A>, but without the moral tone that is striking here. It is well known that the throne was a symbol of divinity in the Orient, and that a king's clothing, bed, and throne were affected with royal and divine mana. Cp. S. Eitrem, <I>Symbolae Osloenses</I>, 10 <A ID="p307x"></A>(1932), 35; R. Labat, <I>Le Caractère religieux de la royauté assyro-babylonienne</I> (1939); P. Schramm, <I>Herrschaftszeichen und Staatssymbolik</I>, 1 (1954), 316‑369; G. Germain, <I>Revue des Études Grecques</I>, 69 (1956), 303‑313; S. Weinstock, <I>Journal of Roman Studies</I>, 47 (1957), 146‑154<!--</A>JOURNAL:JRS:47 copyright thru at least 2017-->. This may explain why it was hybris<!-- sic --> for Alexander to put his feet on the royal table, but not why the throne was so high. A. Alföldi (<I>La Nouvelle Clio</I>, 1950, 537), however, points out that Persian thrones were normally elevated seven steps up, and this one may have lacked its steps. Probably Diodorus's source did not rationalize the anecdote. Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/8*.html#4.15
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(8.4.15‑17)
	</A>
reports that Alexander mentioned this sanctity of the throne, saying that he did not believe in it. Cp. also the second throne incident,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17F*.html#116.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 116.2‑4</A>. See Addenda<!-- zzz -->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note18" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref18
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">18</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#2.17
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 5.2.17</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note19" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref19
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">19</A>
That is, the Pasitigris (<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/5*.html#3.1
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Curtius, 5.3.1</A>: "fourth day"; Arrian, 3.17.1<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note20" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref20
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">20</A>
For the character of the country cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/15C*.html#3.6
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo, 15.3.6 <SPAN CLASS="small">(729)</SPAN></A>. No one else so emphasizes its fertility.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A>
	<A HREF="
