	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pliny, <I>Naturalis Historia</I>, 12.18.33</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note67" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref67
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">67</A>
With some exaggeration, Cleitarchus said of this insect (Jacoby, <I>Fragmente der griechischen Historiker</I>, no. 137, F 14): "It lays waste the hill-country and dashes into the hollow oaks." Tarn (<I>Alexander the Great</I>, 2.90) may be right in preferring the manuscript reading which would make it "smaller than the bee but with a vast appearance," although I do not see precisely what this would mean. Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/2A1*.html#1.14
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo, 2.1.14</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
