onMouseOut="nd();">
5.22‑23</A>;
Arrian, 3.23.7‑9<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note69" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref69
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">69</A>
The same figure is given in
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/6*.html#5.6
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 6.5.6‑10</A>, and Arrian,
3.23.8‑9<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->;
24.5<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note70" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref70
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">70</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/6*.html#5.11
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 6.5.11‑17</A>;
Arrian, 3.24.1‑3<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note71" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref71
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">71</A>
The famous Bucephalus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note72" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">72</A>
Not otherwise mentioned by Diodorus, Demaratus was of some fame. He had served in Sicily with Timoleon, and although no longer young, accompanied Alexander to Asia, fought at the Granicus, and died shortly before Alexander's Indian campaign (Berve, <I>Alexanderreich</I>, 2, no. 253). Plutarch,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/3.html#9.6
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Alexander</I>, 9.6</A>, mentions Demaratus as one of Philip's advisers, but says (6.1)<!-- DON'T LINK --> that Bucephalus was given to Alexander by Philoneicus the Thessalian.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note73" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref73
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">73</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/6*.html#5.18
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 6.5.18‑21</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#44
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 44</A>;
Arrian, 5.19.4‑6
	<!--</A>ARRIAN5-->
(told as an anecdote at the time of the animal's death).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note74" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref74
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">74</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#46
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 46.1</A>, has been generally taken to mean that the queen of the Amazons visited Alexander north of the Jaxartes, in spite of the considerations that this was an odd place for Alexander to linger, and a very long way from the traditional home of the Amazons. This is certainly wrong. In
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#44
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
sect. 44</A>, Alexander was in Hyrcania, and lost and recovered his horse. In
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#45
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
sect. 45</A>, Alexander advanced into


<A ID="p339x"></A>Parthia, and experimented with Median dress. In
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#46
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
sect. 46</A>, the Amazons came.
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#47
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Sect. 47
	</A>
deals again with his Medizing, and
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#48
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
sect. 48
	</A>
with the conspiracy exposed at Prophtasia in Drangianê. That is to say, Plutarch's narrative follows the actual route of Alexander, and the word "here" with which sect. 46 begins must mean Parthia. The reference to Alexander's flying expedition across the Jaxartes at the end of sect. 45, which has misled scholars, is a parenthesis, illustrating Alexander's indifference to physical discomfort.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note75" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">75</A>
If we are to accept that Thallestris and her Amazons existed and had heard of Alexander, there is no insuperable difficulty in supposing that they proceeded from Thermodon on the Black Sea through the valleys of the Phasis and Cyrus Rivers and along the coast of the Caspian Sea. They would have passed through the recently subdued country of the Mardi and overtaken Alexander in Hyrcania (or Parthia, as Plutarch). Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/11E*.html#5.4
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo, 11.5.4</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note76" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref76
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">76</A>
This Amazon visit was a part of the Alexander tradition which Diodorus followed; cp. <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/6*.html#5.24
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Curtius, 6.5.24‑32</A>, and
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#3
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.3.5‑7</A>, both of whom give also the length of the queen's stay as thirteen days. (Justin explains, "<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ut est visa uterum implesse</SPAN>.") Arrian mentions Amazons only in other contexts (4.15.4<!--</A>ARRIAN4-->;
7.13.2‑6<!--</A>ARRIAN7-->) and expresses the doubt that any still existed — especially since they were not mentioned


<A ID="p341x"></A>by Aristobulus or Ptolemy. Plutarch,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#46
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Alexander</I>, 46.1</A>, gives a full list of authorities in favour of or opposed to the visit, but doubts the story
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#46.2
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(46.2)</A>, because it is poorly attested, not because Amazons did not exist. Disbelief in Amazons as such is a modern phenomenon.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note77" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref77
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">77</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/6*.html#6
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 6.6.1‑11</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#3
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.3.8‑12</A>;
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#45
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>, <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#47
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note78" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref78
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">78</A>
He had distinguished himself at Issus
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17B*.html#34.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(chap. 34.2)
	</A>
and gone over to Alexander after Dareius's death (<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/6*.html#2.11
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Curtius, 6.2.11</A>; Berve, <I>Alexanderreich</I>, 2, no. 586).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note79" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">79</A>
The Great Kings wore an upright tiara with a fillet about it; Alexander and the Hellenistic kings wore typically the fillet alone.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note80" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref80
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">80</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/6*.html#6.4
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 6.6.4</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#3
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.3.8</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/6-7.html#45
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 45.1‑2</A>. Plutarch
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Alexandri*/1.html#8
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>De Fortuna aut Virtute Alexandri</I>, 1.8 <SPAN CLASS="small">[329<SPAN CLASS="small">F</SPAN>-330<SPAN CLASS="small">A</SPAN>]</SPAN>)
	</A>
praises Alexander for conciliating his subjects in this way.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note81" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref81
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">81</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/3*.html#3.24
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 3.3.24</A>;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/6*.html#6.8
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
6.6.8</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#3
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.3.10</A>. This retinue


<A ID="p343x"></A>of concubines was part of the traditional ceremonial of the Persian court. Solomon had a similar establishment
	<A HREF="
https://www.newadvent.org/bible/1ki004.htm
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Bible)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(1 Kings 4)</A>, including a harem
	<A HREF="
https://www.newadvent.org/bible/1ki011.htm#3
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Bible)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(1 Kings 11.3)</A>. There were three hundred and sixty of them, according to Ctesias
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Artaxerxes*.html#27
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Plutarch, <I>Artaxerxes</I>, 27)</A>, be three hundred and <SPAN CLASS="whole">sixty-five</SPAN> in the Alexander tradition (Curtius, <I>l.c.</I>). Modern scholars are not inclined to accept this as true, but Alexander's army notoriously did not travel light, and if he had placed his court under a Persian chamberlain, that official would doubtless have attempted to equip it in the proper fashion. Cp. the many anecdotes of Alexander's luxury in Athenaeus, 12.537‑540<!--</A>ATHENAEUS537--> (and of Dareius, <I>idem</I>, 13.557<SPAN CLASS="small">B</SPAN>)<!--</A>ATHENAEUS557-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note82" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref82
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">82</A>
Satibarzanes had been one of the murderers of Dareius, but, after defeating him, Alexander had confirmed him in his satrapy, leaving a small force of Macedonians with him to ensure his good behaviour (Berve, <I>Alexanderreich</I>, 2, no. 697).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note83" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref83
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">83</A>
The city is usually called Artacoana.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note84" HREF="
