38</A>) or by being pierced with javelins
(Arrian, 3.26.3)<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note97" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref97
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">97</A>
The arrest of Alexander was mentioned above
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17B*.html#32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(chap. 32.1)</A>. If the throne were vacant, he would have been the logical person to become king, so that his continued existence involved King Alexander in a certain risk. His wife was one of


<A ID="p351x"></A>the many daughters of Antipater
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#1.7
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Curtius, 7.1.7)</A>, but his <SPAN CLASS="whole">relation</SPAN>&shy;ship to Antigonus is unknown. The latter was King Alexander's representative in Phrygia, but it is likely that his name is a mistake for Antipater's, since Alexander Lyncestes was his son-in‑law (<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#1.7
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Curtius, 7.1.7</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte11.html#7
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 11.7.1</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note98" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref98
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">98</A>
Polydamas and two Arab guides
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#2.17
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Curtius, 7.2.17‑18)</A>. They made the <SPAN CLASS="whole">thirty-days</SPAN>' trip in eleven days
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/15B*.html#2.10
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Strabo, 15.2.10)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note99" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref99
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">99</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#2.35
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 7.2.35‑38</A>;
	<A HREF="
http://wwwumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#5
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.5.4‑8</A>. This name, the "Company of the Undisciplined," is not otherwise reported. The term could be translated also "Unassigned."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note100" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref100
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">100</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#3.3
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 7.3.3</A>;
Arrian, 3.27.4‑5<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note101" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref101
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">101</A>
These are usually called Gedrosians.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note102" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref102
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">102</A>
Arrian
(3.27.5)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->
reports that these tribes were left independent; it may be that this Tiridates was a native of the country (Berve, <I>Alexanderreich</I>, 2, no. 755). Menon became satrap of Gedrosia and Arachosia
(Arrian, 3.28.1)
	<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->
or of Arachosia alone
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#3.5
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Curtius, 7.3.5)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note103" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref103
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">103</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#3.2
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 7.3.2</A>;
Arrian, 3.28.2‑3<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->. They both report that the Macedonian troops were commanded by Erigyius and Caranus, but that Stasanor took over the satrapy in place of the revolted satrap Arsames.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note104" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref104
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">104</A>
Euthycritus was archon at Athens from July of 328 to


<A ID="p355x"></A>June of 327 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> The Roman consuls of 330 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> were L. Papirius Crassus and L. Plautius Venno (Broughton, 1.143). The Olympic Games were those of July 328. Diodorus neglected to name the winner of the foot race, who was Cliton of Macedonia, according to Eusebius, <I>Chronikon</I>. By now, Diodorus's chronology is seriously off; it can have been no later than the autumn of 330 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, "at the setting of the Pleiades"
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/15B*.html#2.10
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Strabo, 15.2.10)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note105" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref105
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">105</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#3.5
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 7.3.5‑18</A>;
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte12.html#5
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Justin, 12.5.9</A>;
Arrian, 3.28.4‑7<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->. This country is the highland of Afghanistan, cold in the winter, but neither in the north nor a plain. According to Aristobulus
(Arrian, 3.28.6)<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->, nothing grew there except terebinth and asafoetida.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note106" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref106
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">106</A>
Curtius's description of these buildings
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#3.8
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(7.3.8‑9)
	</A>
is clearer. He compares the roofs to the keels of ships. The houses were partly <SPAN CLASS="whole">under</SPAN>&shy;ground
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Alexandri*/2.html#9
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Plutarch, <I>De Fortuna aut Virtute Alexandri</I>, 2.9 <SPAN CLASS="small">[340<SPAN CLASS="small">E</SPAN>]</SPAN>)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note107" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref107
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">107</A>
Curtius, also
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#3.10
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(7.3.10‑11)</A>, mentions burying the plants to protect them and the absence of animals and birds.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note108" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref108
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">108</A>
Alexander wintered there in 330/329
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/15B*.html#2.10
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Strabo, 15.2.10)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note109" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref109
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">109</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#3.19
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 7.3.19‑23</A>;
Arrian, 3.28.4<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->. The Hindu Kush, which the ancients tended to confuse with the Caucasus (Arrian, 5.3.1‑4<!--</A>ARRIAN5-->;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/11E*.html#5.5
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Strabo, 11.5.5</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note110" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref110
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">110</A>
This is clearly a mistake, perhaps a scribal mistake, for India, and editors since Reiske have tended to correct the text accordingly. The city was known as Alexandria of the Caucasus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note111" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref111
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">111</A>
Cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17B*.html#note44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">the note on chap. 28, p195, note 44</A>.<!-- Loeb: "note 5", which I adjusted -->


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note112" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref112
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">112</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#3.22
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 7.3.22</A>. The story was rejected by Eratosthenes (<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/11E*.html#5.5
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo, 11.5.5</A>;
Arrian, 5.3.1‑4<!--</A>ARRIAN5-->).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note113" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref113
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">113</A>
These cities are not otherwise mentioned. They may have been outlying forts or fortified villages. It is interesting that they received no Macedonian settlers. Arrian's descriptions (<I>e.g.</I>, 4.4.1<!--</A>ARRIAN4-->) of simple settlements show the same pattern of population. Curtius
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#3.23
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(7.3.23)
	</A>
assigns these seven thousand to Alexandria of Caucasus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note114" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref114
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">114</A>
Continued from
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#81.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 81.3</A>. Curtius, also, breaks his narrative of the revolt, and describes its conclusion and the duel between the leaders after discussing Bessus' assumption of power
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#4.33
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(7.4.33‑4)</A>. Arrian, on the other hand, tells the whole story at once
(3.28.3)<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note115" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref115
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">115</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#4
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 7.4.1‑19</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note116" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref116
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">116</A>
Curtius names this man Gobares (as corrected from the Cobares of the manuscripts).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note117" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref117
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">117</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#5.19
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Curtius, 7.5.19‑26</A>. This is the account of Aristobulus; Ptolemy's version was that he himself had captured Bessus


<A ID="p316x"></A>(Arrian, 3.29.8‑30.5)<!--</A>ARRIAN3-->. Bessus was executed later in Ecbatana (<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Curtius/7*.html#10.10
	"TARGET="Curtius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef1,WIDTH,155)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Curtius, 7.10.10</A>;
Arrian, 4.7.3<!--</A>ARRIAN4-->; cp. <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/5.html#43.3
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Plutarch, <I>Alexander</I>, 43.3</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note118" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#ref118
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">118</A>
Presumably the Oxathres named in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/17D*.html#77.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 77.4</A>.



